ence -- tPART III Thematic Essays -- tCHAPTER 14 ‘Who Did This to Us?’ Blaming the Enemies as Part of Turkey’s Authoritarian Political Culture -- tCHAPTER 15 Nationalism and History, Masks of Violence -- tCHAPTER 16 Public Violence in Turkey from the Nineteenth Century Onwards -- tCHAPTER 17 Structures of Power, Coercion and Violence in Republican Turkey -- tAfterword: Shapes, Legitimation, and Legacies of Violence in the Ottoman Empire and Turkey -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTurkey has gone through significant transformations over the last century—from the Ottoman Empire and Young Turk era to the Republic of today—but throughout it has demonstrated troubling continuities in its encouragement and deployment of mass violence. In particular, the construction of a Muslim-Turkish identity has been achieved in part by designating “internal enemies” at whom public hatred can be directed. This volume provides a wide range of case studies and historiographical reflections on the alarming recurrence of such violence in Turkish history, as atrocities against varied ethnic-religious groups from the nineteenth century to today have propelled the nation’s very sense of itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArmenian Genocide, 1915-1923xInfluence. 0aArmenian massacres, 1915-1923xInfluence. 0aEthnic conflictzTurkeyxHistory. 0aIdentification (Religion)xPolitical aspectszTurkeyxHistory. 0aMinoritiesxCrimes againstzTurkey. 0aMinoritieszTurkeyxHistory. 0aNationalismzTurkeyxHistory. 0aPolitical violencezTurkey. 0aViolencezTurkey. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  aHistory (General), Genocide History, Peace and Conflict Studies.1 aAstourian, Stephan H., econtributor.4ctb4https://